coupled_prompt_600:
Molière is regarded as a master of the erotic and a genius. He was born in 1757, but he first appeared on stage in 1772, at the age of 24, for his play, Le Miroir de la Terre. In 1777, Molière wrote La Femme ou la Puissance, which later became one of the greatest successes in French theatre during the Enlightenment period. It took him four years to write it, from September 1782 to February 1783, when he died.In 1785, after having received numerous complaints and threats, Molière's plays were banned from the theater. This resulted in his public life being almost completely unknown in France until the mid-20th Century, even though they are still performed to this day, most notably in Russia.The following year, Molière published some poems. The next year, he wrote his first novel, Le Grand Tragedy (also known as Les Fêtes de Doude), which was dedicated to the Emperor Napoleon I, who had just returned from the second half of the Seven Years War. It was called, "an epic which portrays the struggle of good against evil." Le Tragedy lasted for 1,547 pages. The novel was soon followed by another, Les Misérables (translated as Les Miséricains) which was published in 1801. In 1803, Le Grand Misérables was republished as an eight volume set and in 1806, as a single volume titled Les Misérables.
